cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  Playing "standard Lebensohl", we can only make an invitational bid at the 3-level when OUR suit is higher-ranking than the suit overcalled.

So if YOUR suit is higher-ranking than theirs (ie: you can bid your suit at the 2-level over their overcall), then the 2-level bid is just competitive and a slow bid of your suit at the 3-level is invitational.

If, however, their suit is higher-ranking than yours, then the slow sequence is just competitive and you effectively "lose" the ability to show an invitational hand.

This is one of the limitations of "standard" Lebensohl.

It is the main area in which TRANSFER LEBENSOHL benefits over normal Lebensohl.

That is something we'll be looking at next week, but you need to understand the basic concept first and you will find many more people (unfortunately) who play Lebensohl, but not Transfer Lebensohl.

You might think it odd that that I'm showing you normal Lebensohl when I am actually suggesting you use Transfer Lebensohl instead.

This system, however, also makes extensive use of normal Lebensohl as well as Transfer Lebensohl, so you need to know BOTH methods.

As more people play normal Leb rather than Transfer Leb, you definitely need to get "normal" Leb under your belt first.

Lastly, worth noting in passing that Transfer Lebensohl is NOT the same thing as Rubensohl.

Rubensohl and Transfer Lebensohl are SIMILAR, but there are subtle (but critical) differences between them. Those who want more detail should see the^*h http://ocp.pigpen.org.uk/Leb.php##XferLeb ^*n Transfer Leb notes^*x.

I make no particular claim as to which is "better", but I prefer Transfer Leb.|
