If the opponents intervene in a Minor suit, then it can be a matter of partnership agreement as to whether responder promises both Major suits with a Cue-bid, or guarantees only one 4-card Major.

eg: 1NT - (2@D) - 3@D |cp|gr|at|^s (below is repeated from earlier)|cp||at|

I prefer that it only GUARANTEES one Major (but might have both).  I tend to play that when denying a stop in their suit, by making a FAST cue-bid, I am more likely to have BOTH unbid Majors. 

So    1NT - (2@D) ^j   - 3@D   is denying a  @D  stop and so probably has BOTH Majors, 
but   1NT - (2@D) - 2NT(Leb) - 3@C(forced) - 3@D   is  PROMISING (showing) a  @D  stop and now might only have
^k     ONE 4-card Major.             (SLOW SHOWS    -    FAST DENIES)

You might think you could play this the other way around, but there is a very good reason why not: If you HAVE a stop in their suit and move to make a SLOW cue of their suit, you cannot be pre-empted by them, since you can always show your hand (by doubling their 3-level bid or bidding 3NT).  If you do it the other way around then after their 3-level pre-empt you are stuck.


