fp|t-title|at|Standard Lebensohl  -  Summary|fp||at|^^^^|
cp|red|at|^*bOliverC:^*n|cp||at|  So what have we learned today?   Lebensohl uses 2NT as a special bid after  1NT - (2x) - ???

It simply asks partner to bid 3@C.  Responder's hand type is only clarified with their rebid over 3@C.

2NT of itself doesn't promise anything in particular

2-level suit bids are always just "competitive".

Bids at the 3-level are split into 2 types (Fast and Slow) depending on whether Responder uses the 2NT-3@C relay sequence or not.

FAST bids of a new suit at the 3-level are always FORCING, whilst SLOW bids of a new suit are competitive (if Opps' suit higher ranking than ours) or invitational (if their suit is lower-ranking).

Cue-bids of Opps' suit are always Staymanic, showing 4-card interest in any unbid Major(s).

FAST cues deny a stop in Opp's suit and SLOW cues promise a stop.

ANY cue of their suit promises game-going values.

Bids of 3NT all show game-going values and deny 4-card interest in any unbid Majors.

FAST 3NT bids DENY a stop in Opps' suit (often based on a long running Minor), whilst SLOW 3NT bids promise a stop in their suit.|
